05854nam a22009015i 9780231557078DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315570787 a10.7312/mitc207662doi  a(DE-B1597)642846  a(OCoLC)1355883769  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ1236.5.B6bM583 2023 7aSOC0560002bisacsh04a305.48/896081223/eng/202212221 aMitchell-Walthour, Gladys L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of Survival :bBlack Women Social Welfare Beneficiaries in Brazil and the United States /cGladys L. Mitchell-Walthour. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b15 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBlack Lives in the Diaspora: Past / Present / Future00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1 THE POLITICS OF SURVIVAL -- t2 SUPPORT OF SOCIAL WELFARE PROGRAMS, STIGMA, AND RESISTANCE -- t3 PERCEPTIONS OF CLASS, SKIN COLOR, AND GENDER DISCRIMINATION -- t4 ARE POOR BLACK WOMEN TO BLAME FOR CONSERVATIVE POLITICIANS? -- t5 CONCLUSION Are Poor Black Women the Hope for Progressive Politics? -- tAPPENDIX -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPoor Black women who benefit from social welfare are marginalized in a number of ways by interlocking systemic racism, sexism, and classism. The media renders them invisible or casts them as racialized and undeserving “welfare queens” who exploit social safety nets. Even when Black women voters are celebrated, the voices of the poorest too often go unheard. How do Afro-descendant women in former slave-holding societies survive amid multifaceted oppression?Gladys L. Mitchell-Walthour offers a comparative analysis of how Black women social welfare beneficiaries in Brazil and the United States defy systems of domination. She argues that poor Black women act as political subjects in the struggle to survive, to provide food for their children and themselves, and challenge daily discrimination even in dire circumstances. Mitchell-Walthour examines the effects of social welfare programs, showing that mutual aid networks and informal labor play greater roles in beneficiaries’ lives. She also details how Afro-descendant women perceive stereotypes and discrimination based on race, class, gender, and skin color. Mitchell-Walthour considers their formal political participation, demonstrating that low-income Black women support progressive politics and that religious affiliation does not lead to conservative attitudes.Drawing on Black feminist frameworks, The Politics of Survival confronts the persistent invisibility of poor Black women by foregrounding their experiences and voices. Providing a wealth of empirical evidence on these women’s views and survival strategies, this book not only highlights how systemic structures marginalize them but also offers insight into how they resist such forces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American womenxPolitical activity. 0aPoor womenxPolical activityzBrazil. 0aPoor womenxPolitical activityzBrazil. 0aPoor womenxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aWomen, BlackxPolitical activityzBrazil. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh  aAfrican Diaspora.  aBlack feminist thought.  aBlack studies.  aBrazil.  aUnited States.  aclassism.  acolorism.  acomparative sociology.  adiscrimination.  agender studies.  amutual aid.  apolitical identity.  aprecarity.  aracial identity.  aresistance.  asocial safety nets.  asocial welfare.  asurvival.  asystemic racism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter